theories/FacePolygon.v

# extract_rings_valid R5 / general assembler, slice 3e: orientation
# classification of face rings (docs/face-orientation.md).  Lifts slice-3d's
# signed-area primitive to rings/faces: ring_signed_area2 + ring_ccw/ring_cw
# classifier (exclusivity, trichotomy); ring_signed_area2_of_chain (a face ring's
# area = its chain's, via ring_edges_of_closed_chain); and the headline
# twin_face_chain_signed_area -- the face built from the TWIN darts walked in
# reverse has the NEGATED signed area, so the face across each edge is oppositely
# oriented (the combinatorial heart of outer vs hole).  The geometric meaning of
# the sign + analytic hole_inside_outer are deferred (§4).  No Admitted; standard
# three-axiom classical-reals base.
theories/FaceOrientation.v

# extract_rings_valid R5 / general assembler, slice 2a: the angular comparator
# on darts (docs/extract-rings-proof-structure.md §5 step 1, the cyclic-order
# primitive; docs/dart-angular-order.md).  Orders the outgoing fan BY ANGLE
# without a materialised atan2 -- a half-plane + Azimuth.turn_sign (cross)
# comparator -- and proves it a STRICT TOTAL ORDER on directions in general
# position: dir_lt_irrefl / _asym / _trans (via the ring certificate
# vcross_chain_cert + nra) / _total, lifted to darts as dart_lt_*.  The cyclic
# `next` built on this order, and the face_of orbit + its finiteness (the §9
# crux), are deferred later slices.  No Admitted; axioms = the allowlisted
# classical-reals pair via first_half_dec's real-order decision.
theories/DartAngularOrder.v

# extract_rings_valid R5 / general assembler, slice 2b: the cyclic `next`
# (rotational successor) on the outgoing dart fan (docs/dart-next.md).  Reflects
# the slice-2a order into bool (dir_ltb/dart_ltb + *_spec bridges), defines
# list_min and `next` (minimal strictly-greater dart, wrapping to the global min
# at the fan maximum), and proves next WELL-DEFINED on the fan: next_in (orbit
# closure), next_base (stays at the vertex), next_advances (advances in angle
# while a greater dart exists).  Minimal-successor correctness, injectivity /
# cyclic-permutation, and the face_of orbit FINITENESS (§9 crux) are deferred
# (slice 2c).  No Admitted; axioms = the allowlisted classical-reals pair.
theories/DartNext.v

# extract_rings_valid R5 / general assembler, slice 2c: the rotational-successor
# CORRECTNESS spec of `next` (docs/dart-next-spec.md).  Under fan_ok (proper +
# general-position fan), proves list_min is a genuine lower bound (fold_min_lb /
# list_min_lb -- the fold-minimum is correct under a strict total order) and
# pins `next` down: next_min_successor (the minimal strictly-greater dart) and
# next_wrap_least (global min on wrap).  Injectivity / cyclic-permutation and the
# face_of orbit FINITENESS (§9 crux) are deferred (slice 2d).  No Admitted;
# axioms = the allowlisted classical-reals pair.
theories/DartNextSpec.v

# extract_rings_valid R5 / general assembler, slice 2d: INJECTIVITY (and
# surjectivity / cyclic-permutation) of `next` on the outgoing fan
# (docs/dart-next-injective.md).  In a cyclic angular order each dart has a
# unique predecessor (the maximal dart below it, or the global max on wrap), so
# next_no_collision / next_injective: next is injective on a fan_ok fan; and
# next_surjective: on a NoDup fan it is onto (injective endo on a finite set),
# hence a cyclic permutation.  This is what makes the face_of walk a genuine
# CYCLE.  The face_of orbit of next o twin + its FINITENESS (§9 crux) is deferred.
# No Admitted; axioms = the allowlisted classical-reals pair.
theories/DartNextInjective.v

# The Jordan-curve seam for point_in_ring_correct, examined head-on
# (docs/jct-vacuity-finding.md).  Proves the corpus's
# geometric_interior_stdlib is identically false because
# connected_in_complement uses discontinuous paths
# (geometric_interior_stdlib_vacuous), so the JCT-conditional headline is
# only vacuously satisfiable.  Supplies the corrected continuity-carrying
# definitions + the genuine JCT_two_components_cont Prop (thesis-scale,
# stated not proved), and shows the corrected relation is non-degenerate
# (far_points_connected_cont).  Pure-R; no Admitted/Axiom/Parameter.
theories/JordanCurveSeam.v

# The continuous-component spine of the polygonal Jordan-curve seam, built on
# JordanCurveSeam's continuity-carrying definitions.  Proves
# connected_in_complement_cont is an equivalence relation (continuity_glue for
# the concatenation join), in_bounded_component_cont is a component invariant,
# and -- as a corollary, NOT thesis-scale -- no_path_from_interior_to_exterior
# (interior trapped relative to exterior).  far_point_not_interior is the
# honest continuous analogue of the vacuity witness.  The genuine remaining
# seam (ray-parity characterises the continuous interior) is the named Prop
# parity_characterises_interior_cont, wired into the non-vacuous headline
# point_in_ring_correct_jct_cont.  Pure-R; no Admitted/Axiom/Parameter.
theories/JCT.v

# Special-case JCT, slice 1 (docs/extract-rings-proof-structure.md §11): the
# ray-parity COMPUTATION for an axis-aligned rectangle.  Proves
# point_in_ring p (rect_ring x0 y0 x1 y1) <-> (y0<py<y1 /\ x0<=px<x1) by finite
# evaluation of the inductive ray_parity_odd over the four edges (horizontal
# edges are ray-parallel and never cross; vertical edges give the parity).
# The combinatorial/computational half of parity_characterises_interior_cont
# for rectangles; JCT-free.  Pure-R, three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/RectangleJCT.v
# Special-case JCT, first sloped-edge family: the axis-aligned right triangle.
# Generalises RectangleJCT's ray-parity computation to a ring with a sloped
# edge (the hypotenuse).  point_in_ring_right_triangle_iff: parity test = the
# half-open triangle interior (y0<py<y1 /\ x0<=px<hyp_x py).  Reuses the
# rectangle ray-parity reduction lemmas + axis-aligned edge characterisations;
# only e_hyp_cross_iff and hyp_x_bounds are new.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/RightTriangleJCT.v
# Special-case JCT: the right-triangle separation, unconditionally, via the
# SeparationField engine.  Field tri_min = Rmin(Rmin(px-x0)(py-y0)) s_hyp with
# s_hyp the AFFINE inward distance to the hypotenuse.  Gives
# right_triangle_parity_characterises_interior (point_in_ring <-> geometric
# interior for triangle interiors), the second fully-closed JCT family.
# Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/RightTriangleSeparation.v
# Special-case JCT, slice 2d (docs/extract-rings-proof-structure.md §11): the
# rectangle separation, UNCONDITIONALLY.  Encodes box membership as a single
# continuous field box_min (>0 inside, =0 on the edge skeleton, <0 outside) and
# uses Stdlib IVT -- a complement path never hits 0, so it cannot change sign,
# hence stays inside.  Discharges RectangleJCT.rect_confines and gives the full
# unconditional rect_parity_characterises_interior.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/RectangleSeparation.v
# Special-case JCT, slice 3a: the IVT separation engine, abstracted from the
# rectangle.  separation_via_field -- a continuous scalar field that is >0
# inside, =0 on the edge skeleton, <0 outside, with bounded positive region --
# forces in_bounded_component_cont.  The reusable foundation for future ring
# families (convex polygons via min-inward-signed-distance).  Re-derives the
# rectangle (rect_in_bounded_component) through the engine.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/SeparationField.v
# Convex specialisation of the IVT separation engine: conv_min = Rmin over a
# list of half-plane inward slacks.  conv_min_pos_iff, continuity_pt_conv_min_path,
# and the convex_separation wrapper.  The reusable layer that box_min and tri_min
# instantiate; convex polygons supply edge half-planes + zero-set/bound facts.
# Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/ConvexField.v
# Special-case JCT: separation half for an ARBITRARY (CCW) triangle, parametric
# over its three vertices.  Field gtri = Rmin of the three inward signed areas;
# the area-sum + barycentric ring identities turn the bound and the edge
# parametrisation into nra/field.  gtri_interior_is_geometric: interior points
# are geometric interior points (via separation_via_field).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/GeneralTriangleSeparation.v
# Special-case JCT: foundation + minimal hypothesis for the arbitrary-triangle
# ray-parity, plus the RED non-vacuity check on the separation engine.
# edge_cross_sign (edge_crosses_ray <-> signed-area sign); gtri_parity_spec (the
# minimal parity hypothesis) + gtri_in_ring_imp_geometric (conditional headline);
# engine_produces_inhabited_interior (geometric_interior_cont is INHABITED, vs the
# refuted geometric_interior_stdlib).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/GeneralTriangleParity.v
# Showcase: the "hat" aperiodic monotile (Smith-Myers-Kaplan-Goodman-Strauss
# 2023) as a concrete non-convex 13-gon Ring (hexPt shear, exact sqrt 3 coords).
# ring_closed / 13-edge count / >=4 vertices / genuine NON-CONVEXITY (boundary
# turns both ways via Orientation.cross).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/HatMonotile.v
# Showcase: the "Spectre" strictly-chiral aperiodic monotile's defining
# ingredient -- a CURVED edge -- formalized.  curved_edge_central_symmetry: any
# midpoint-odd profile makes the edge invariant under 180-degree rotation about
# the chord midpoint (the reflection-free mating property).  Concrete sine_edge.
# Three-axiom (cos/sin clean).  No Admitted.
theories/SpectreCurvedEdge.v
# Besicovitch-Kakeya, Phase A (docs/besicovitch-kakeya-plan.md): finite,
# polygonal Perron-tree stages.  perron_stage n : list Ring is the apex-fan over
# a unit base subdivided into 2^n equal pieces (2^n triangles, each a closed
# Ring).  Proves: exactly 2^n triangles; every triangle ring_closed + >=4
# vertices (DCEL/ray-parity ready); non-degenerate (signed area 1/2^n);
# DIRECTION COVERAGE -- the 2^n triangles carry 2^n pairwise NON-PARALLEL
# directions (perron_stage_directions_distinct); contained in the unit square;
# directions invariant under the future sliding moves.  No measure theory
# claimed (deferred to Phase D).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/PerronStage.v
# Besicovitch-Kakeya, Phase B (docs/besicovitch-kakeya-plan.md): DCEL / overlay
# integration of the Perron-tree stages.  Each stage triangle is a DCEL
# face-walk -- its edge list is a closed_chain that ring_of_chain round-trips
# (perron_tri_closed_chain / _chain_roundtrip / _face_walk_core) -- and is
# UNCONDITIONALLY ring_simple (perron_tri_ring_simple, via sip_shared_no_cross:
# two non-collinear segments from a shared vertex never cross properly).  Hence
# every triangle is a valid_polygon and the whole stage is a valid_geometry
# (perron_geometry_valid), a legitimate Overlay.boolean_op operand.  Three-axiom.
# No Admitted.
theories/KakeyaOverlay.v
# Besicovitch-Kakeya, Phase C (docs/besicovitch-kakeya-plan.md): a FROZEN
# regression anchor over perron_stage 5 (32 triangles).  kakeya_anchor_count
# (= 32); kakeya_anchor_valid_geometry; kakeya_anchor_all_ring_simple; thin
# slivers of uniform area 1/32 that stay strictly positive (kakeya_anchor_area /
# _area_pos -- near-collinearity); perron_consecutive_share_cevian (edge-to-edge
# overlap); perron_area_decreasing (area 1/2^n shrinks with depth -- the finite
# shadow of the Phase-D area -> 0, not attempted here).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/KakeyaExample.v
# Besicovitch-Kakeya, the Perron area-REDUCTION step, finite (no measure):
# sliding the sub-triangles preserves direction coverage
# (perron_slid_directions_distinct -- translation leaves the apex-cevian
# direction fixed) and each slid piece keeps its area 1/2^n (perron_slid_area),
# so total area drops only via OVERLAP -- and sliding creates it
# (slid_pieces_overlap: (1/4,1/4) is interior to two slid depth-1 pieces).  The
# union-area arithmetic itself is Phase D (measure).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/KakeyaSlide.v

# Why ring_simple is NOT sufficient for JCT_two_components_cont
# (docs/jct-bowtie-counterexample.md).  The self-touching figure-8 "bowtie"
# (two triangles meeting only at the origin) is ring_simple, ring_closed and
# has >= 4 vertices -- it passes EVERY structural premise -- yet its
# complement has THREE components, so two-components fails.  Proves
# bowtie_ring_simple, bowtie_origin_degree_four, the parity misclassification
# (both lobes "inside"), and bowtie_refutes_two_components_modulo_separation:
# the conclusion is contradictory given the (thesis-scale, taken-as-hypothesis)
# pairwise component-separation facts.  Pure-R; no Admitted/Axiom/Parameter.
theories/JCT_Counterexample.v

# Why no_horizontal_edge_at is NOT enough for ray-parity to characterise the
# interior (docs/jct-vertex-grazing-counterexample.md).  A convex diamond and
# its centre B = (0,0): the rightward ray grazes vertex (1,0), so the strict
# y-straddle counts neither incident edge and parity is EVEN -- yet B is
# interior.  no_horizontal_edge_at holds at B (the diamond has no horizontal
# edge), so it fails to exclude the graze.  diamond_refutes_parity_seam shows
# the JCT.v seam parity_characterises_interior_cont cannot hold at both B and a
# correctly-classified A in the same component (geometric_interior_cont is a
# component invariant; point_in_ring is not).  GREEN: ray_avoids_vertices is the
# missing generic-position guard (parity_characterises_interior_cont_strict).
# Pure-R; no Admitted/Axiom/Parameter.
theories/JCT_VertexGrazingCounterexample.v

# Why the JCT parity seam NEEDS no_horizontal_edge_at
# (docs/jct-horizontal-edge-counterexample.md).  A valid simple L-shaped
# "notch" hexagon with a horizontal edge at y=1, and the exterior point
# pext=(-1,1): ray-parity counts only the far right edge (the genuine left
# crossing happens degenerately along the horizontal edge) so point_in_ring
# pext = true, yet pext escapes to infinity leftward (notch_pext_not_interior).
# RED notch_refutes_parity_without_guard: point_in_ring disagrees with
# geometric_interior_cont. GREEN: no_horizontal_edge_at pext notch is false, so
# the existing seam parity_characterises_interior_cont already excludes it --
# the guard is necessary. Pure-R; no Admitted/Axiom/Parameter.
theories/JCT_HorizontalEdgeCounterexample.v

# Buffer/noder pipeline, end-to-end seam S1 (docs/buffer-noder-pipeline.md):
# the conditional headline buffer_correct_conditional -- Minkowski-dilation
# spec buffer_spec, concrete offset_curve (via BufferOffset), abstract noder
# + extractor, composing the overlay graph spine.  Plus buffer_contains_input
# and buffer_spec_monotone.  Pure-R, three-axiom footprint.  No Admitted.
theories/BufferCorrectness.v
# extract_rings_valid R1+R2 (docs/extract-rings-proof-structure.md): the
# combinatorial core of ring assembly, grounded in BufferAssembly's closed
# chains.  ring_of_chain (face walk -> ring); face_walk_closed /
# face_walk_min_points / ring_edges_of_closed_chain / face_walk_core
# (closure + min-points + edge fidelity).  Axiom-free (pure combinatorics).
# No Admitted.  ring_simple / hole_inside_outer (analytic shell) not here.
theories/RingExtract.v

# extract_rings_valid R5 (docs/extract-rings-proof-structure.md §7 +
# docs/extract-flatten-counterexample.md): the naive OverlayGraph.extract
# flatten is NOT a valid ring assembler (RED) and the trace that fixes it
# (GREEN).  extract_unordered_not_valid / extract_single_not_valid -- a closed
# triangle boundary given out of walk order (resp. a single edge) flattens to a
# non-closed (resp. 2-vertex) ring, so extract emits ~valid_polygon, refuting
# the deferred extract_rings_valid conclusion for the stub.  ring_of_chain_
# traces_valid_shape -- the SAME triangle, walk-ordered and traced by
# RingExtract.ring_of_chain, is ring_closed /\ ring_has_minimum_points.  The
# assembly analogue of RingSimple.not_ring_simple_bowtie.  No Admitted.
theories/ExtractFlattenCounterexample.v
# extract_rings_valid R3 (docs/extract-rings-proof-structure.md): the
# bounded-component structure underlying the hole-count heuristic.
# connected_in_complement is an equivalence relation (_refl/_sym/_trans);
# in_bounded_component is a component invariant (in_bounded_component_iff);
# not_in_bounded_component_intro refutes boundedness from unbounded
# reachability.  JCT-free.  The geometric "face-interior -> bounded" rung
# (= H1/JCT) is carried as a downstream hypothesis, not admitted here.
theories/BoundedComponent.v
# extract_rings_valid: the ring_simple condition.  ring_simple_of_subset --
# a ring drawn from a pairwise-non-crossing (noded) arrangement is simple
# (the post-noding guarantee); not_ring_simple_bowtie -- the raw self-crossing
# offset is NOT simple (verified counterexample, why noding is required).
# Pure-R.  No Admitted.
theories/RingSimple.v
# extract_rings_valid R6 (docs/extract-rings-proof-structure.md): compose
# R2 (RingExtract) + ring_simple (RingSimple) into valid_polygon and
# discharge BufferCorrectness.buffer_correct_conditional's H_valid.
# valid_polygon_of_noded_chain (hole-free, no JCT); chain_extractor_spec +
# H_valid_of_chain_extractor; buffer_correct_hole_free (H_valid discharged,
# only H_bridge remains).  valid_polygon_with_holes carries the H1/JCT hole
# clause as a hypothesis.  Pure-R.  No Admitted.
theories/ExtractBufferRings.v
# Completed analytic shell of extract_rings_valid (extract-rings-proof-structure
# R7): discharge the holes' combinatorial+simplicity conditions from their being
# noded chains too, shrinking the with-holes residual to the SINGLE named
# hole_inside_outer (JCT) clause.  valid_polygon_noded_shell /
# H_valid_of_chain_extractor_holes / buffer_correct_with_holes.  Pure-R, 3-axiom.
theories/ExtractRingsShell.v
# Buffer headline semantic bridge (docs/buffer-noder-pipeline.md): the
# buffer_spec d-dilation algebra (empty/append/monotone) and the
# decomposition of H_bridge into soundness + completeness.
# buffer_correct_hole_free_split reduces the hole-free buffer headline to
# exactly those two geometric directions (H_valid already discharged).
# Pure-R.  No Admitted.
theories/BufferBridge.v
# The SOUNDNESS half of H_bridge at the boundary-distance level: offset/bevel
# join boundary stays within d of the corner (ball_convex + bevel_point_dist),
# while the miter apex escapes the corner's d-ball (miter_apex_overshoots_vertex
# via the closed miter_length_sq) -- the precise reason soundness needs a
# non-miter join / the miter limit.  Pure-R, three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/BufferBridgeSound.v
# Completeness mirror: the chord-approximated join UNDERSHOOTS the corner d-ball
# (chord_midpoint_dist_sq_90 = d^2/2 < d^2), dual to the miter overshoot --
# the chord leaves an uncovered sliver of the d-neighbourhood.  Pure-R, 3-axiom.
theories/BufferBridgeComplete.v
# Round-join arc on the corner d-circle (round_arc_dist_sq_on_circle = d^2):
# closes both H_bridge directions at the corner, and the buffer_corner_trichotomy
# capstone (chord d^2/2 < arc d^2 < miter 2 d^2).  Pure-R, three-axiom.
theories/BufferBridgeRound.v
# Stage 4b depth labelling (EdgeLabel reused as interior-side flags; keep-
# boundary rule = SymDiff) + factorisation of the full H_bridge through the
# depth region (extract_realizes_depth /\ depth_region_is_buffer), with the
# empty base case closed.  Pure-R, three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/BufferDepth.v

# Why depth_region (BufferDepth.v) needs a CLOSED-BOUNDARY guard
# (docs/buffer-depth-enclosure-counterexample.md).  depth_region runs
# ray_parity_odd over the kept edges with no constraint that they form a closed
# boundary.  The open "spur" (a single kept edge) makes depth_region non-
# component-invariant: p1=(-1,1) and p2=(-1,3) are complement-connected yet get
# opposite verdicts (spur_depth_not_component_invariant, RED).  Its kept
# boundary is the degenerate open ring spur_ring = [(0,0);(0,2)], which is not
# ring_closed; a closure-guarded depth predicate excludes it
# (spur_excluded_by_closure_guard, GREEN).  Pure-R; no Admitted/Axiom/Parameter.
theories/BufferDepthEnclosureCounterexample.v

# depth_region's closed-boundary guard (#91) is necessary but not sufficient
# (docs/buffer-depth-horizontal-edge-counterexample.md).  Reusing the #86 notch
# as the (closed) kept boundary of a graph G_notch, depth_region G_notch pext is
# true (the ray runs along the horizontal kept edge) yet pext is exterior
# (depth_region_horizontal_refutes, RED).  A no_horizontal_edge_at guard on the
# kept boundary excludes it (Gnotch_excluded_by_no_horizontal_guard, GREEN).
# Pure-R; no Admitted/Axiom/Parameter.
theories/BufferDepthHorizontalEdgeCounterexample.v

# Completes depth_region's guard set: the vertex-graze case
# (docs/buffer-depth-vertex-graze-counterexample.md).  Reusing the #85 diamond
# as the (closed, horizontal-edge-free) kept boundary of G_diamond, A=(0,1/2)
# and B=(0,0) are complement-connected yet get opposite depth_region verdicts
# (depth_region_vertex_not_invariant, RED) because B's ray grazes vertex (1,0).
# A ray_avoids_vertices guard on the kept boundary excludes it
# (Gdiamond_excluded_by_ray_avoids_guard, GREEN).  With #91/#93 this pins the
# full guard set. Pure-R; no Admitted/Axiom/Parameter.
theories/BufferDepthVertexGrazeCounterexample.v

# REFACTOR: the guarded depth-region predicate + depth/interior bridge
# (docs/buffer-depth-guarded.md).  Folds the #91/#93/#95 guards into
# kept_boundary_wellformed and re-points the depth seams onto it (additive; the
# existing BufferDepth theorems are untouched).  depth_region_is_geometric_
# interior_guarded is the depth analogue of point_in_ring_correct_jct_cont:
# for a well-formed kept boundary, depth_region = geometric_interior_cont under
# the named JCT seam parity_characterises_interior_cont_strict (not discharged).
# buffer_H_bridge_factor_guarded re-points the H_bridge onto the guarded seam.
# Pure-R; no Admitted/Axiom/Parameter.
theories/BufferDepthGuarded.v

# Phase 4 Session 2: SQL/MM CIRCULARSTRING / COMPOUNDCURVE foundational
# types (CircularArc, CurveSegment, CurveRing, CurvePolygon,
# CurveGeometry) + validity predicates + chord approximation bridge
# (chord_approx_arc / chord_approx_segment / chord_approx_ring /
# to_geometry).  Option B (chord approximation, confirmed in
# docs/audit-phase4-chord-overfitting.md §7).  Six Qed-closed
# structural lemmas; no Admitteds; no Classical_Prop.classic.
theories/CurveGeometry.v
# Structural faithfulness of the curve->Phase3 linearisation bridge: a valid
# (closed) CIRCULARSTRING/COMPOUNDCURVE ring chord-approximates to a ring_closed
# Phase-3 ring (chord_approx_ring_closed), lifting to to_geometry outer/hole
# rings.  Pure-R, three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/CurveLinearise.v

# Phase 4 Session 3: arc orientation predicate.  Two R-side tools:
# cross_R_pt (Stdlib lift of cross_R_BP) and inCircle_R (the 4-point
# lifted determinant from Shewchuk 1997).  Arc orientation built on
# top: arc_side_chord, arc_interior_side, arc_orient (ArcInterior /
# ArcExterior / ArcOnChord trichotomy).  Plus arc_coord_safe R-side
# precondition for future b64 work.  No new typeclass (HasOrient2d
# deferred).  Eleven Qed-closed lemmas; no Admitteds; no classical-prop
# pulls.
theories/ArcOrient.v

# Phase 4 Session 4: arc-chord and arc-arc intersection predicates
# (R-side, Prop-valued).  Defines arc_span_contains (Option S: chord
# cross-product sign for arcs < pi), arc_chord_intersects (existence
# of a point on chord segment that is also on the arc -- uses the
# existing `between` predicate from theories/Segment.v),
# arc_arc_intersects (existence of a point on both arcs), and
# chord_crosses_arc_circle (a SUFFICIENT-condition positive filter
# under IVT: opposite inCircle_R signs guarantee a crossing; NOT a
# rejection filter -- both endpoints can be outside while the chord
# still crosses twice).  Six Qed-closed structural lemmas (boundary
# span membership + symmetry).  No new typeclass (HasArcIntersect
# parallel deferred per Intersect_b64_exact.v §6 dovetail).  Soundness
# theorem (IVT-based existence from sign-change) deferred to follow-up.
# No Admitteds; no classical-prop pulls.
theories/ArcIntersect.v

# Phase 4 Session 5: arc-in-hot-pixel predicate (R-side).  Defines
# pixel_bottom_left / _bottom_right / _top_right / _top_left corner
# helpers parameterised by (C : Point, scale : R).
# arc_passes_through_hot_pixel: six-way disjunction (four arc-chord
# edge crossings + two endpoint containment tests).
# arc_touches_hot_pixel: the SPEC predicate (existential -- a point on
# the arc is in the pixel).  Eight Qed-closed structural lemmas: six
# disjunct-introduction lemmas + two endpoint soundness lemmas
# (passes_through endpoint case => touches).  Edge-crossing soundness
# direction deferred (depends on S4's arc_chord_intersect_sound
# IVT gap).  Half-open convention mirrors Phase 2's in_hot_pixel
# (bottom/left CLOSED, top/right OPEN).  No Admitteds; no
# classical-prop pulls.
theories/ArcHotPixel.v

# Phase 4 Session 6: sagitta + chord approximation foundations (R-side).
# Defines arc_radius_sq, chord_half_length_sq, chord_half_length, and
# sagitta (using Rmax to keep the sqrt argument non-negative
# definitionally).  Headline lemma: arc_center_equidistant proves the
# three control points are equidistant from arc_center (closed via
# `field` after unfolding the explicit circumcenter formula).
# Fifteen Qed-closed lemmas covering sagitta non-negativity,
# sagitta_le_arc_radius, and the bridge arc_radius = sqrt arc_radius_sq.
# The full chord_approx_error_bound headline is deferred to a follow-up
# (depends on arc_radius_sq_ge_chord_half_length_sq + perpendicular-
# bisector geometry + S4's IVT-blocked soundness).  No Admitteds.
theories/ArcChordApprox.v

# Phase 4 Session 7: arc overlay correctness conditional headline.
# The Option B headline -- same epistemic position as Phase 3's
# overlay_ng_correct_conditional.  Defines arcs_of: CurveGeometry ->
# list CircularArc, max_sagitta: CurveGeometry -> CurveGeometry -> R
# (the chord-approximation tolerance), arc_close_to_curves: the
# conclusion predicate (q is within eps of some arc point in A or B).
# Headline `arc_overlay_correct_chord_approx` Qed-closed via case-split
# on BooleanOp under two named gap hypotheses (H_A_bridge, H_B_bridge
# encapsulating the deferred chord_approx_error_bound + polygon
# traversal lifts).  Plus six Qed-closed structural lemmas
# (max_sagitta_nonneg, arcs_of_nil/_cons/_segment_chord/_segment_arc,
# forward corollary).  No Admitteds; no classical-prop pulls.
theories/ArcOverlay.v

# IVT gap closure: chord_crosses_arc_circle_implies_circle_intersection.
# Defines chord_point (parametric chord at t in [0,1]) and
# inCircle_along_chord (inCircle_R applied to the parametrised chord,
# viewed as R -> R).  Proves derivability via Ranalysis_reg's `reg`
# tactic, then lifts to global continuity via `derivable_continuous`,
# then applies Stdlib's IVT_cor (sign-product form) to discharge:
# sign change at endpoints implies a circle-crossing chord point.
# Strengthening to arc_chord_intersects (adding arc_span_contains on
# the witness) is deferred to a separate session.  Eight Qed-closed
# lemmas/theorems; no Admitteds; pulls Ranalysis chain (sig_not_dec,
# sig_forall_dec, functional_extensionality_dep -- README-allowlisted).
theories/ArcIntersectIVT.v

# Flocq-dependent modules (built only in the container; require coq-flocq).
# Live in theories-flocq/ rather than theories/ so the host CI grep for
# Admitted markers does not pick up in-progress soundness bridges.
-Q theories-flocq NTS.Proofs.Flocq
theories-flocq/Validate_binary64.v
theories-flocq/Orientation_b64.v
# binary64 <-> R bridge.  Lifts Flocq's Bplus_correct / Bminus_correct /
# Bmult_correct to b64_plus / b64_minus / b64_mult under a no-overflow
# precondition.  Critical-path module identified in
# docs/audit-shewchuk-stages.md: unlocks the simplifier R-bridge, the
# orient2d arithmetic identities, and Shewchuk Stages B/C of orient2d.
theories-flocq/B64_bridge.v
# Forward-looking wrapper module.  Promotes the `Local Notation b64_*`
# boilerplate to module-level, registers Flocq typeclass instances for
# binary64 (Prec_gt_0, Valid_exp, Monotone_exp), and re-exports
# pre-instantiated Flocq lemmas (ulp_le_abs, ulp_FLT_0,
# error_le_half_ulp_round, etc.) plus helpers accumulated during
# Stage D (round_minus_swap, etc.).  Placed here -- right after its
# upstream B64_bridge -- so downstream files (Orient_b64_exact,
# Intersect_b64_exact, HotPixel_b64) can `Require Import B64_lib`
# instead of repeating the Local Notation boilerplate.
theories-flocq/B64_lib.v
# R-side arithmetic identities for b64_orient2d, proved via composition
# of the per-op lifts in B64_bridge.  First downstream consumer of the
# bridge; establishes the pattern other identities will reuse.
theories-flocq/Orient_b64_R.v
# Soundness bridge for the Stage A filter.  Today: decoder consistency
# (filter's sign matches B2R sign of the rounded value).  Cross_R-valued
# soundness for the general bounded regime is documented as a deferred
# Path 1 in docs/soundness-strategy.md.
theories-flocq/Orient_b64_sound.v
# Cross_R-valued soundness in the integer-coordinate exact regime (Path 2
# from docs/soundness-strategy.md).  Headline:
#   orient2d_inputs_int_safe P0 P1 Q ->
#   match b64_orient_sign_filtered P0 P1 Q with
#     OrientRPos  => 0 < cross_R_BP P0 P1 Q
#   | OrientRNeg  => cross_R_BP P0 P1 Q < 0
#   | OrientRZero => cross_R_BP P0 P1 Q = 0
#   | _           => True end.
# Bit-exact -- no rounding error -- for |coord| <= 2^25 integer inputs.
theories-flocq/Orient_b64_exact.v
theories-flocq/Orient_b64_exact_full.v
# Phase 1 first slice: binary64 segment-pair intersection predicate built
# on top of Stage A filter.  Five-valued result (None / Point / Collinear /
# Nan / Uncertain).  Ships the predicate, structural lemmas (decidability,
# totality, 10-way distinctness, NaN-propagation), and a first soundness
# theorem in the integer regime: IntersectNone implies the underlying
# R-side segments don't share a point (composing decoder soundness with
# the rejection-sound direction of theories/Intersect.v).
theories-flocq/Intersect_b64.v
# Phase 1 Scope A: first-stage bit-exactness for the binary64 intersection-
# point computation (the prefix of Cramer's rule before division).  Ships
# the safety predicate, the four first-stage exactness lemmas (qp0, qp1,
# dx, dy), and a minimal `HasIntersect` typeclass + BPoint instance as the
# thin leading wire for future curve primitives.  Round-chain identity
# (Scope B) and forward-error bound (Scope C) are deferred.
theories-flocq/Intersect_b64_exact.v
# R-bridge soundness for the binary64 simplifier.  Ships R-projection
# wrappers (B2R_bp, map_B2R_bp, is_finite_bp, point_int_safe,
# points_int_safe), the b64_cross / b64_orient2d connector, the
# integer-regime exactness lemmas for b64_cross and b64_dist_sq, plus
# the dist_sq_R_BP witness.  Splits the soundness obligations away from
# the structural file (Validate_binary64.v) so the four Stdlib classical-
# reals axioms are only paid when the soundness surface is consumed.
theories-flocq/Validate_binary64_bridge.v
# Stage D bridge module: discharges Pff2Flocq's section parameters for
# binary64 (specifically: choice_sym for round_mode mode_NE = ZnearestE).
# One-time work that unblocks every subsequent Pff2Flocq lift.  Ships
# b64_Fast2Sum_correct as the first Stage D primitive landed via the
# bridge -- validates the scout's "subsequent lifts ~30 lines" estimate.
theories-flocq/B64_Pff_bridge.v
# Shewchuk Theorem 13, the pathB exact-cancellation brick (toward the deferred
# fast_expansion_sum_nonoverlap_shewchuk).  b64_TwoSum_exact_of_format_sum:
# when B2R x + B2R y is representable, b64_TwoSum x y = (exact sum, 0).
# b64_TwoSum_sterbenz_exact: the opposite-sign similar-magnitude (Sterbenz)
# instance -- zero error term.  This is the arithmetic core of the documented
# pathA-OR-pathB invariant widening; the invariant re-proof itself is not here.
theories-flocq/B64_TwoSum_sterbenz.v
# Shewchuk Theorem 13, obligation O1' (docs/shewchuk-thm13-pathb-plan.md §7):
# the residue-granularity lemma.  residue_ge_half_ulp: for opposite-sign
# Sterbenz-position operands, the exact sum is 0 or >= 1/2 ulp(vC) -- the bound
# that lets a nonzero pathB cancellation residue dominate the sub-ulp output, so
# clause (a) survives without a strengthened dominance invariant.  Standalone
# Flocq ulp arithmetic; no cascade machinery, no deferred-headline dependence.
theories-flocq/B64_residue_granularity.v
# Stage D bridge: Dekker's TwoProduct is EXACT (zero low part) on the
# integer-coordinate regime.  b64_Dekker_exact_of_format (representable
# product => high = product, low = 0) + b64_Dekker_int_exact (the integer
# instantiation, |a*b| <= 2^prec).  This is the missing brick that lets the
# proven, UNCONDITIONAL fast_expansion_sum_nonoverlap_shewchuk_int_safe_two_pairs
# apply to real Dekker output -- no dependence on the deferred general headline.
theories-flocq/Orient_b64_dekker_int.v
# Stage D expansion arithmetic foundations.  Ships the data structure
# (b64_expansion = list binary64), non-overlap predicate, sum/sign
# definitions, and the structural lemmas.  HEADLINE
# `sign_of_expansion_correct` is deferred; this is where the GENUINELY
